metaData.descriptionCS: Within a specified time limit, the child views a completed puzzle and selects three response options that, when combined, reconstruct the puzzle.

questions.title: Demonstration Item
questions.topInstructionsHTML:
Say, I am going to choose three of these pieces (point across response options) that go together to make this puzzle (point to completed puzzle). The three pieces have to go next to each other, not on top of each other.

Say, After I look at all of the pieces, I choose these three (point to response options 1, 2, and 6). If I put them together in my mind, they would make this puzzle (point to completed puzzle).

questions.title: Sample Item
questions.correctInstructionsHTML:
Correct response [3, 4, and 5]:

Say, That’s right. If you put these three pieces next to each other (point to response options 3, 4, and 5), they will make this puzzle (point to completed puzzle). You have to turn this piece (point to response option 4) in your mind to make it fit. Let’s try some more.
questions.incorrectInstructionsHTML:
Incorrect response:

If the child chooses response options 3, 5, and 6, say, That’s not quite right. The pieces have to go next to each other, and not on top of each other. If you put these three pieces next to each other (point to response options 3, 4, and 5), they will make this puzzle (point to completed puzzle). You have to turn this piece (point to response option 4) in your mind to make it fit. Let’s try some more.

If the child chooses any other combination of incorrect response options, say, That’s not quite right. If you put these three pieces next to each other (point to response options 3, 4, and 5), they will make this puzzle (point to completed puzzle). You have to turn this piece (point to response option 4) in your mind to make it fit. Let’s try some more.
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Say, Now you try one. Which three pieces (point across response options) go together to make this puzzle (point to completed puzzle)?
